1.3 Counts

  • This dataset is comprised of 50 bootstrap datasets.
  • Within each bootstrap dataset, there are boot_data %>% group_by(bootstrap) %>% summarize(num_shuffles=max(shuffle)+1) %>% distinct() %>% select(num_shuffles) %>% distinct() shuffles of cosine distances between a base/target pair.

2 Bootstrap Process

  1. Create \(m\) bootstrap datasets \(D_{m=1, 2, ..., z}\) by randomly sampling patients from the original 40,000 UCSF patients’ notes dataset. By resampling with replacement on patients, we are being explicit about the correlation structure of notes written for a single patient.

  2. From those \(m\) bootstrap datasets, consider the plug-in estimator \(\hat{\theta}_m=f(D_m)\) for a quantity of interest \(\theta\). Calculate \(\hat{\theta}_m\) for each bootstrap dataset \(D_m\).

  3. Calculate the mean \(\bar{x}(\hat{\theta}_m)\) and standard deviation \(s(\hat{\theta}_m)\).

  4. The \((1-\alpha)\times 100\)% confidence interval for \(\theta\) can be constructed using

\[ \bar{x}(\hat{\theta}_m) \pm \Phi(1-\alpha) \times s(\hat{\theta}_m) \] where \(\Phi\) is the normal distribution CDF.

3 Statistics

We can consider several quantities as \(\theta\) depending on our research question.

3.1 Single Base-Target Pairs

If we would like to understand whether or not there is evidence for a base-target pair to be synonymous and antonymous, we consider these hypotheses and

\[ H_0: \mu_\text{Base, Target} = 1 \\ H_1: \mu_\text{Base, Target} \neq 1 \]

want to use the bootstrap statistic

\[ \hat{\theta}_m = \frac{1}{k} \sum_{k} \text{cos-dis}(\text{Base, Target})_k \] where \(k\) represents the index of a cosine distance/data shuffle within a bootstrap dataset. (Each shuffle corresponds to an estimated cosine distance between a base and target.)

3.2 Two Bases and Single Target

Should we wish to understand if two bases have equal cosine distances from the same single target, then we need to consider another bootstrap statistic.

\[ H_0: \mu_\text{Base 1, Target} = \mu_\text{Base 2, Target} \\ H_1: \mu_\text{Base 1, Target} \neq \mu_\text{Base 2, Target} \] We will opt to study the mean difference of cosine distances. We will calculate the statistic

\[ \hat{\theta_m} = \frac{1}{k} \sum_{k} \text{cos-dis}(\text{Base 1, Target})_k - \text{cos-dis}(\text{Base 2, Target})_k \] for each of the \(m\) bootstraps. Then, we can test whether or not this difference is 0 or not.

3.3 Three Bases and Single Target

If we are interested in testing

\[ H_0: \mu_\text{Base 1, Target} = \mu_\text{Base 2, Target} = \mu_\text{Base 3, Target} \\ H_1: \text{At least one } \mu_\text{Base, Target} \text{ does not equal the others.} \] we can consider using the same bootstrap statistic for each of the possible pairs \(P = [ \{1,2\}, \{1,3\}, \{2,3\} ]\):

\[ \hat{\theta_m} = \frac{1}{k} \sum_{k} \text{cos-dis}(\text{Base 1, Target})_k - \text{cos-dis}(\text{Base 2, Target})_k \]

then correct the confidence intervals using Bonferroni significance level \(\frac{\alpha}{\text{Number of Bases}}\) to control for family-wise error rate.

3.3.1 Bonferroni

We will correct the confidence intervals we create for each base word using Bonferroni’s correction.

\[ \text{p-value}_\text{Bonferonni} = \frac{\text{1-Confidence Level}}{\text{Number of Tests}} \] If we are creating (1-\(\alpha\)) % CI’s, then we will be considering this p-value.

\[ \text{p-value}_\text{Bonferonni} = \frac{1-0.95}{3} \approx 0.0167 \]

We can get the normal quantile to create our confidence intervals.

\[ \Phi(0.0167) \approx 2.13 \]

3.4 Three Bases and Synonymous/Class Targets

In order to combine synonymous targets or targets within a class, we propose a bootstrap statistic that uses inverse-variance weighting or precision weighting. Using the \(m^{th}\) bootstrap dataset, for each ethnic base term, calculate

\[ \text{Precision-Weighted Average (PWA)} = \sum_k \frac{a_1\text{[Average Cosine Distance]}_1 + ... + a_k\text{[Average Cosine Distance]}_k}{a_1 + ... + a_k} \] where \(a_k = \text{var}(\text{Average Cosine Distance})^{-1}\). This is a weighted average of the mean cosine distances of each of the synonymous/class targets. We are essentially weighting the cosine distances between bases/targets by how variable they are.

To review, we will have 3 precision weighted averages per bootstrap dataset. Then, we can use our pairwise bootstrap statistic!

\[ \hat{\theta_m} = \text{PWA}_{A} - \text{PWA}_B \] We can then construct confidence intervals around the difference in precision-weighted average cosine distances. We will Bonferonni correct them, so they are approximately 98% confidence intervals.

\[ \bar{x}(\hat{\theta_m}) \pm 2.13 \times \text{SD}(\hat{\theta_m}) \]

4.4 Three Bases and Synonymous/Class Targets

We will calculate the difference in mean precision-weighted averages for each base/base pair. Here is some pseudocode.

# create list to save all difference in precision-weighted averages
all_differences = []

# using each bootstrap dataset, calculate pwa difference
for bootstrap_m in all_bootstraps:
  for target_f in all_synonym_targets:
    # calculate mean, sd, ak
    mean_1, mean_2 = mean(cosine_distance_1), mean(cosine_distance_2)
    sd_1,   sd_2   = sd(cosine_distance_1), sd(cosine_distance_2)
    ak_1,   ak_2   = sd_1^-2, sd_2^-2
  
  # calculate precision-weighted averages
  pwa_1 = sum(ak_1 * mean_1) / sum(ak_1)
  pwa_2 = sum(ak_2 * mean_2) / sum(ak_2)
  difference_pwa = pwa_1 - pwa_2
  
# create confidence interval
mean(difference_pwa) - 2.13*sd(difference_pwa)
mean(difference_pwa) + 2.13*sd(difference_pwa)

4.4.1 Confidence Intervals

I am going to do the tests I showed above. These tests are Bonferroni corrected.

4.4.1.1 Violence Subclass

4.4.1.1.1 95% CI for PWA
violence_pwa_test <- boot_data_long %>%
  filter(subclass == 'violence') %>%
  group_by(bootstrap, target_word, base_word) %>%
  
  summarize(cdk = mean(cosine_distance),
            sdk = sd(cosine_distance),
            ak  = 1/sdk^2) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(bootstrap, base_word) %>%
  
  mutate(ak_cdk = cdk * ak) %>%
  summarize(theta_k = sum(ak_cdk, na.rm=TRUE) / sum(ak, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  
  ungroup() %>%
  reshape2::dcast(bootstrap ~ base_word, value.var='theta_k') %>%
  
  summarize_at(.vars=c('african_american', 'caucasian', 'hispanic'),
               .funs=make_ci)

  reshape2::dcast(base_word ~ attr, value.var='pwa_average') %>%
  mutate(avg = (lb + ub)/2) %>%
  mutate(se=(ub-avg)/1.96) %>%
  mutate(lb_se = avg - se) %>%
  mutate(ub_se = avg + se) %>%
  mutate(base_word=factor(base_word, levels=c('african_american', 'caucasian', 'hispanic')))

# Plot the data
adjec_pwa_test_plottable %>%
    ggplot(aes( color = base_word)) +
      geom_hline(yintercept=1, lwd=2, alpha=0.5) +
    geom_linerange(aes(x = base_word, ymin = lb, ymax = ub),
                   size=2, alpha=0.7, position = position_dodge(width=0.6)) +
  geom_point(aes(x=base_word, y=avg),
             pch=15, position = position_dodge(width=0.6)) +
    
  scale_x_discrete(limits = rev) +
    coord_flip() +
  
    # Remove extraneous labels
    ylab('') +
    xlab('') +
    
    # Fix Legend
    scale_color_manual(name='Base word',
                       labels=c('African-American', 'Caucasian', 'Hispanic'),
                       values=c( '#61B329', '#1874CD',  '#FFC125')) +
    theme_bw()
